{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cfad38be-7b0e-4d80-b792-07a858fa782d","content":"The project doesn't exist in the current directory, but here's how to configure it. Create or edit `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout (the standard for local MCP servers).\n- **`command` / `args`** — Uses `dotnet run` to build and launch your project. Paths are relative to the workspace root.\n- If you publish a self-contained binary instead, replace `command` with the path to the executable and drop the `args`.\n\nMake sure your server reads from stdin and writes to stdout using the MCP protocol (e.g., via the `ModelContextProtocol` or `Microsoft.Extensions.AI` SDK).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"91df1b44-b23a-4f27-821f-87c2dc30426b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist at that path. But the user said they built it there. Regardless, I can still give them the configuration guidance for `mcp.json`. Let me provide the answer based on what they've told me.","outputTokens":322,"requestId":"C044:3F44A7:1D7FE97:211CD44:6A07C2D8"},"id":"6ec3d754-aa6c-4c33-8bfa-8c48ea442290","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:05:37.633Z","parentId":"e3ab2e60-12ee-4373-bede-757e9c52dd49"}
